Figure 3(a) shows the typical form of the total velocity field around a particle, illustrating the predominantly dipole nature of the field due to the density difference between particle and liquid which causes relative motion between the particle and the bulk liquid (at some distance from the particle). The circulation of the liquid in the region around the particle is clear. The axial component of the velocity (uz) is shown in Fig. 3(b), demonstrating that the particle’s greater inertia causes it to have a lower velocity in the propagation direction than that of the liquid at some distance from the particle. These velocity fields can be used to determine the vorticity11\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
